        <tr>
          <td colspan="2"><span
class="postbody">I tried to post this on the WoW general forums to the mass of idiots, but when I hit 'Submit' I got *SURPRISE* "Login Failure". I gave up after an hour of trying to post.
<br />

<br />
I got to 57, and quit from pure fucking boredom. Switched to this only a day after trying the trial, earlier this week. I used to be a medium (3-5 hours a day, couple days a week) EQ player, and "community" was something you were a part of whether you liked it or not. You all interacted, crossed paths and communicated. You knew people and recognized a lot of names. Shit, after being in WoW for what.. 3 months since retail? I still only know a handful of people and see new faces all the time. This game is simply Diablo 3 in the Warcraft world. Talent trees are ripped from Diablo 2 and seemingly just as useless for most of them. Rerolling another character is the same exact game all over again. I played Horde, and the fastest way to level was to get your ass to the Barrens and follow the same exact path as the previous character. Not much option either.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Adventure, excitement... WoW provides not these things.
<br />

<br />
Hi. You don't know me, I don't expect you to. Sense of community is somewhat low in WoW due to the fast paced grouping and greediness of most players, save just a few people you may meet in the game. I think some of you can agree to that. Most don't even post on these boards.
<br />

<br />
I'd just like to say my piece and split. I know this will probably be met with boatloads of  fanbois flaming me, telling me how wrong or stupid I am, or have some other smart a$$ comment thats supposed to make me feel bad that I'm leaving a half developed game. If you disagree with the last statement, you're dreaming.
<br />

<br />
I never played the game prior to retail.
<br />

<br />
I never read much about the game prior to retail, other than what my friend told me about it, who had the beta.
<br />

<br />
He enticed me to buy the game, and join them on Archimonde, the "most popular" PvP server. That "PvP" was fun and what "everyone" was doing. I was intrigued.
<br />

<br />
I bought it at retail.
<br />

<br />
I started with this character. Wow! Levelling is fast, and easy! I can solo! I have a quest log and map to boot! 
<br />

<br />
Boom, half the game servers vanish for a bit, typical of most MMO launches, restart on another server until Archimonde is fixed. Played a warrior to 15 before deciding it was really boring and monotonous, not to mention frustrating that I had trouble handling one mob of my level or lower while any other class could knock them down easily.
<br />

<br />
Archimonde is back, so I get back with the shaman. I have no trouble playing the game at all, save the server downtimes, lag, and bugs. The main draw here for me was that I could solo and not be forced into grouping, unlike EQ1 where you pretty much had to group beyond the early levels.
<br />

<br />
I joined a PvP server for two reasons:
<br />

<br />
1. Friends
<br />
2. PvP reward/honor system (oh shit suprise, not here lol)
<br />

<br />
I also was enticed into the game by the lure of Battlegrounds, which probably isn't even close to being finished.
<br />

<br />
So, I continue playing the game.
<br />

<br />
I'm in my 40s, and I start noticing the problems with this game.
<br />

<br />
1. No death penalty. This means that upon death, players don't care that they died, because nothing at all has punished them for dying, other than 10% durability, big deal. No death penalty means that most players will not give a crap to perform better in a group, make poor choices and wipe more. I mean why bother tightening skills? There is no penalty for dying, like XP/loot loss. If you resulted in consequence from PvE death, I can assure you the skill levels of most people would begin to rise, they'd start caring.
<br />

<br />
2. Levelling is TOO fast. Yeah at first, you think, well this is great I don't have to play 20 hours a day to level up. Well, when I started grouping and people didn't know how to play their classes, such as a mage asking 'what is polymorph?' (at level <span style="font-weight: bold">42!</span>- seriously.) when I asked why he wasn't doing that to adds; or when a melee does not assist the main tank, clearly this proves the learning curve is virtually non-existant. People don't know HOW to play in a group, some don't even know their class. They are too busy blowing through levels because to them, the higher level they are, the better they must be, right? I've been grouped with 60s who had no clue how to perform in a group. No scale of difficulty = no real learning process. That hurts later on.
<br />

<br />
3. Tradeskills have low returns on them, unless you have a ton of time to put into doing them to make some kind of profit. I got over 250 in engineering before realizing more money was going out than would ever come in. Cut them a break and give them more things to sell. How about failing a tradeskill once in a while as well? My orc can't be that fuckin smart to never fail and have to retry something at least ONCE.
<br />

<br />
4. Asian farmers are hurting the AH, seriously. Check the prices of wool stacks on Archimonde for example. Anywhere from 1.3-2g last time I checked, a week ago. Runecloth stacks would only fetch me 1.2g. its not just this either, there are inflated prices on a lot of things. Golden rule: if its purple, they will pay.
<br />

<br />
5. Severe lag problems resulting from large scale cross-faction (20+) fights in capitol cities that affect the entire server. NOT fun if it makes the server crash while you're hip deep in an instance. Its not my computer either, its 3.4ghz top of the line etc, I'm tired of people saying get a better computer.
<br />

<br />
6. Talents. I've respecced about 6 times I believe, and I love being penalized to pay high prices because I didn't fully understand that half of the talents are junk and wouldn't really benefit me at all. I think a 2-3 week cooldown on respec is more reasonable, I sure don't make boatloads of gold. Most I ever had was enough to get a mount, and not much more.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Now as you can see, I'm not guilded. This isn't because I ninja loot, kill steal or anything of the sort. I'm just not guilded. I was going to attempt to get in one of the big raiding guilds on the server, because I want something to do with people who know what they are doing, but they seem to appear and dissapear bi-weekly/monthly. Where is the comraderie in this game? Why don't people stick together? Greed? In turn, this makes grouping severely hard beyond level 55+ in the instances like BRS, MC, Strat or Scholo (though most refuse to do Strat and Scholo due to crappy 
<br />
loot, bugs, etc). I am sorry but I do NOT have 2+ hours to stand around in Ogrimmar trying to put together a group or raid to do one of these instances just to advance gearwise and quest wise. Especially since like I said before, in pick up groups its common that nearly half the players won't have a clue what they are doing and make it more painful than it needs to be.
<br />

<br />
Also I thought a feature would be to raid someones city for fun and excitement? A long ass fight for 22g (King Bronzebeard) and some runecloth sure is exciting, not to mention seeing my ms go up to over 2000 while I'm clear on the other side of the world. "Someone's raiding! Yay!"
<br />

<br />
Just another good player that is leaving...
<br />

<br />
If you want to know, I switched to EQ2 after playing the new trial. I like it a lot and really love how its all setup. I guess its just more my style of RPG. Not preaching, just saying. Give the new trial a try before bashing it, they've really made some good changes. All that really hinders it is the somewhat steep system requirements, which is basically the memory management (512 is ok, 1 gb is ideal).
<br />

<br />

<br />
1. Challenge
<br />
2. Difficulty
<br />
3. Danger
<br />

<br />
These don't hurt an MMO, you know. At first I thought WoW was the best invention since pussy, but after a while I realized that the above three things did not exist at all, and in my opinion are the BASIC FOUNDATIONS of a good RPG.
<br />

<br />
I also am completely SICKENED at one of the new blue posts concerning the new realms. And I quote:
<br />

<br />
"These give new players the opportunity to begin their adventures in Azeroth on untouched realms. They also give existing players who are looking to move from high-population realms <span style="font-weight: bold">the ability to create new characters on fresh, low-population realms.</span> "
<br />

<br />
SLIME. I REFUSE to reroll off a high pop server to a new one, we should be able to transfer characters, especially when some of the insane lag pisses me off and makes me log off for the day. fuck this game. the end.</span><span
class="gensmall"></span></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
  </tr>
